ENCORE Wine patch -- sync layered attributes to the scaled surface (win32u)

Ported from shibco/ableton-linux patches/0015 (shibco / shibacomputer,
cade@parare.al) -- a fix to LGPL-2.1+ Wine's win32u. Regenerated against
wine-11.13; behaviour unchanged.

scaled_surface_flush() forwarded color_key/alpha_bits/alpha_mask to the
target x11 surface only on shape changes. Layered windows with no shape --
e.g. JUCE DropShadower soft-shadow windows around plugin popups -- never get
their per-pixel alpha across, and x11drv_surface_flush() ORs 0xff000000 into
every pixel, turning premultiplied mostly-transparent black into opaque black
rectangles. Sync the layered attributes on every flush (a no-op when they are
unchanged). Upstream-PR candidate.
See shibco notes/ABLETON-WINE-PLUGIN-TITLEBAR-BUG.md.

diff --git a/dlls/win32u/dce.c b/dlls/win32u/dce.c
index 5e8d82aed3..ba845df5c0 100644
--- a/dlls/win32u/dce.c
+++ b/dlls/win32u/dce.c
@@ -201,11 +201,16 @@ static BOOL scaled_surface_flush( struct window_surface *window_surface, const R
         HRGN hrgn = map_dpi_region( window_surface->shape_region, surface->dpi_from, surface->dpi_to );
         window_surface_set_shape( surface->target_surface, hrgn );
         if (hrgn) NtGdiDeleteObjectApp( hrgn );
-
-        window_surface_set_layered( surface->target_surface, window_surface->color_key,
-                                    window_surface->alpha_bits, window_surface->alpha_mask );
     }
 
+    /* Keep the target surface's layered attributes in sync on every flush, not only on
+     * shape changes: layered windows without a shape (e.g. JUCE popup-menu drop-shadow
+     * windows, per-pixel alpha via UpdateLayeredWindow) otherwise never propagate
+     * alpha_mask to the driver surface, which then composites them as opaque black.
+     * window_surface_set_layered only invalidates the target when a value changed. */
+    window_surface_set_layered( surface->target_surface, window_surface->color_key,
+                                window_surface->alpha_bits, window_surface->alpha_mask );
+
     window_surface_flush( surface->target_surface );
     return TRUE;
 }
